Cell["\<\
Simon\[CloseCurlyQuote]s algorithm (Simon, 1997) was the first quantum \
algorithm featuring an exponential speed-up over the best known classical \
algorithm for a specific problem. The algorithm is known to have inspired the \
quantum factorization algorithm. Furthermore, it has recently been shown that \
Simon\[CloseCurlyQuote]s algorithm can be used to break symmetric-key \
cryptosystems.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1713612190,ExpressionUUID->"5d7f0f70-c119-4980-a9b9-b8ced55f8d15"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In Simon\[CloseCurlyQuote]s problem, we are given a function ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"f", ":", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], "n"], "\[RightArrow]", 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], "n"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"86c5957d-6101-4c36-b37e-d853bbbaaf7a"],
 " and a secret string ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["s", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "caf81fb8-47d1-4bc6-990c-8d984c163892"],
 " of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4712d29c-1470-4f18-90f2-8e62ae689d39"],
 " bits. For all ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"x", ",", 
    RowBox[{"y", "\[Element]", 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"0", ",", "1"}], "}"}], "n"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"7c2a2228-06ea-4733-8680-9188b6dbbd9c"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"f", 
     RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"f", 
     RowBox[{"(", "y", ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dc894e50-10b8-493e-8026-d8f195ee0e0c"],
 " if and only if ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"y", "=", 
    RowBox[{"x", "\[CirclePlus]", "s"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "965da70b-369c-495a-90f6-8fca129fbd58"],
 ". Note that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["f", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "47671dae-b0dc-4ca0-914d-e74b1edb4006"],
 " is either one-to-one (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"s", "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "cc2c9104-74f0-438c-bb57-beec88456fa8"],
 ") or two-to-one (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"s", "\[NotEqual]", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "33eef9c7-3306-4b50-bc83-446c7d4f4cec"],
 "). The task is to find the secret string ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["s", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0a4786f4-f0d7-41d8-95ea-b9084dcb0b9f"],
 " with as few queries to function ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["f", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "daad1de9-3674-4272-a309-c828ec782376"],
 " as possible. Classically, one needs queries to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"f", 
    RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b27fc7a7-f63b-4530-8d77-a533c80ab52b"],
 " with up to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["2", 
     RowBox[{"n", "-", "1"}]], "+", "1"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b1d070f3-3d33-4c97-9e9a-1e582604af54"],
 " different inputs. (More precisely, one needs order of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SqrtBox[
    SuperscriptBox["2", "n"]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1b9213af-332d-4826-8501-5e6ad73f093d"],
 " queries to encounter a pair of two bit strings leading to the same result \
with probability greater than 1/2. The number being ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SqrtBox[
    SuperscriptBox["2", "n"]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ebb2f376-fbb9-493f-a9d1-42290eaa8c45"],
 " rather than ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2", "n"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5359366c-fca9-48bd-91d4-a8f7d0c71808"],
 " is related to the so-called \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]birthday paradox\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote].) Unlike the ",
 ButtonBox["Deutsch-Jozsa problem",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/DeutschJozsaAlgorithm"],
 ", Simon\[CloseCurlyQuote]s problem is known to be hard to solve, even \
probabilistically."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->776887413,ExpressionUUID->"a845ecd5-6123-4bbb-986a-6b39d2a999e5"],

